      "result": "\u003coutput\u003e\n{\n  \"rating\": 3,\n  \"summary\": \"The iter-3 delta addresses several ATX iter-2 warnings but two of the five claimed fixes are structurally unsound: the ordering test still cannot detect an insertion-order-preserving implementation, and the multi-provider env lockstep test is self-referential. The bedrock dedup canonical tests are solid and the TG shadow assertions are correct. No blocking issues; two warnings remain.\",\n  \"findings\": [\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py:688-742\",\n      \"issue\": \"W-test-ordering-absoluteness NOT fixed. The fixture feeds aux specs in alphabetical insertion order: `vision` (index 0) then `web_extract` (index 1) â€” both in the legacy `aux_specs` list and the canonical `aux_inputs` tuple. The pinned `expected_order = ['title_generation', 'vision', 'web_extract']` is alphabetical AND matches insertion order. An insertion-order-preserving render implementation (no sort at all) would emit `title_generation` (default, prepended) then `vision` then `web_extract` â€” identical to `expected_order`. The test therefore does NOT fail if the render function never sorts. The fix only works if you feed the specs in reverse-alphabetical order (e.g., `web_extract` before `vision`) so that an insertion-order-preserving path would produce `['title_generation', 'web_extract', 'vision']` â‰  `expected_order`. This directly contradicts the iter-2 acceptance criterion.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Swap the fixture order: pass `web_extract` before `vision` in both `aux_specs` and `aux_inputs`. The expected_order stays `['title_generation', 'vision', 'web_extract']`. Only a correct sort-by-role implementation will then pass.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py:814-864\",\n      \"issue\": \"W-test-env-lockstep-multi is self-referential. The sole assertion is `self._emitted_env_keys(legacy_env) == self._emitted_env_keys(canonical_env)`. If both template families regress in lockstep â€” e.g., both silently drop `OPENAI_API_KEY` after a refactor â€” the sets remain equal and the test stays green. The test verifies inter-family consistency but pins nothing against a known-correct expected set. This is the classic 'both parties agree on wrong answer' pattern.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add a literal expected_keys assertion before the equality check: `expected_keys = {'ANTHROPIC_API_KEY', 'OPENROUTER_API_KEY', 'OPENAI_API_KEY', 'HERMES_INFERENCE_PROVIDER'}` then `assert expected_keys == self._emitted_env_keys(legacy_env)`. The existing equality check can remain as a redundant lockstep guard.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"warning\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py:485-543\",\n      \"issue\": \"W-test-bedrock-dedup-uncovered: both new tests target only the canonical path (`render_hermes`). The legacy template (`hermes.env.j2`) has its own Jinja-level bedrock dedup logic (lines 44-65 of the template) which is not independently tested in `TestLegacyEnvMultiProvider`. `TestLegacyEnvMultiProvider` covers openrouter same-key and different-key dedup but has no bedrock+bedrock equivalent. There is also no lockstep test comparing bedrock conflict WARNING output across both families, unlike `test_same_type_conflict_warning_in_both_families` for openrouter.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add `test_bedrock_dedup_same_creds_no_warning` and `test_bedrock_dedup_diff_creds_emits_warning` to `TestLegacyEnvMultiProvider` mirroring the new canonical tests. Optionally add a bedrock lockstep analogue to `test_same_type_conflict_warning_in_both_families`.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py:347-370\",\n      \"issue\": \"W-test-tg-shadow-independence: the standalone canonical test `test_explicit_title_generation_aux_shadows_default` still only asserts the override model is present â€” it does not assert `'claude-haiku' not in str(tg)`. The lockstep test was correctly updated, but the canonical-only test remains weaker. If `TestLegacyCanonicalLockstep` is ever split out, this gap becomes invisible.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add `assert 'claude-haiku' not in str(tg)` after line 369 in `TestCanonicalMultiProvider.test_explicit_title_generation_aux_shadows_default` to mirror the lockstep test's defense-in-depth.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"severity\": \"suggestion\",\n      \"location\": \"tests/test_hermes_multi_provider_templates.py:485-513\",\n      \"issue\": \"The same-creds bedrock dedup test only checks `AWS_ACCESS_KEY_ID` count and value. It does not assert `AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY='secret-SAME'` appears exactly once or that `AWS_DEFAULT_REGION` is present. A regression that duplicated the secret-key or region line would pass.\",\n      \"suggestion\": \"Add `assert env.count('AWS_SECRET_ACCESS_KEY=') == 1` and `assert \\\"AWS_DEFAULT_REGION='us-east-1'\\\" in env` to fully pin the single-triplet contract.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"recommendations\": [\n    \"Fix the ordering fixture: feed aux specs in reverse-alphabetical order (web_extract before vision) to make the sort contract detectable.\",\n    \"Pin the multi-provider env lockstep test against a literal expected key set so dual-regression cannot slip through.\",\n    \"Add legacy-path bedrock+bedrock dedup tests in TestLegacyEnvMultiProvider to match the canonical coverage just added.\"\n  ],\n  \"metadata\": {\n    \"files_reviewed\": 4,\n    \"domain\": \"test-coverage\",\n    \"commits_in_delta\": 1,\n    \"delta\": \"e7ceae3..70c09df\"\n  }\n}\n\u003c/output\u003e",
